						<p>
							My research interests lie in the cryosphere, including both land-ice (glaciers) and sea-ice. I prefer working with statistical models over numerical ones and enjoy collecting data in the field. To this end, I have accompanied Prof. <a href="http://caos.cims.nyu.edu/object/davidholland">David Holland</a> (NYU) to Sermilik Fjord, Greenland to collect oceanographic and seismic data near Helheim Glacier. 
</p>
<p>I am particularly interested in mathematical and statistical techniques for solving problems with Big Data. I also have experience in fitting statistical models to extremely noisy data and bivariate fitting with planes to rotatable 3D scatter plots. These are programmed in Python and can be shared upon request - please <a href="contact.html">contact me</a>! I am also interested in interdisciplinary research, e.g. applying physical and mathematical models/tools to biological or chemical processes.
						</p>
<p>
My current work with my research supervisor, Dr. <a href="https://www.whoi.edu/profile.do?id=tmaksym">Ted Maksym</a> (WHOI), will be looking at sea ice formation and polynyas in the Ross Sea in Antarctica.
</p>


					</div>
